let _markdown = "\n\n## Protocol Comparison\n\nChoosing the right chromatin conformation capture method depends on your biological question, sample availability, and budget.\n\n## Decision Guide\n\n<Mermaid\n  chart={`graph TD\n  A[Start] --> B{Protein-specific<br/>interactions?}\n  B -->|No| C[Hi-C]\n  B -->|Yes| D{Input cells<br/>available?}\n  D -->|>10M cells| E{Budget?}\n  E -->|High| F[ChIA-PET]\n  E -->|Limited| G[HiChIP]\n  D -->|<1M cells| G\n`}\n/>\n\n## Quick Comparison\n\n| Feature                 | Hi-C                | ChIA-PET          | HiChIP          |\n| ----------------------- | ------------------- | ----------------- | --------------- |\n| **Input cells**         | 1-10M               | 10-50M            | 100K-1M         |\n| **Protein specificity** | No                  | Yes               | Yes             |\n| **Cost**                | $$                  | $$$$              | $$              |\n| **Best for**            | Genome architecture | Specific proteins | Low-input loops |\n\n## When to Use Each\n\n### Hi-C\n\nUse for genome-wide chromatin architecture, TAD identification, and compartment analysis.\n\n### ChIA-PET\n\nUse for high-confidence protein-specific loops with abundant sample material.\n\n### HiChIP\n\nUse for protein-specific interactions with limited input material or large cohort studies.\n\n## Chr3D Support\n\nChr3D provides unified analysis for all three protocols with consistent APIs and workflows.\n";
